<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" ?>
<section xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="s_product2">
	<title>Arbitrary products</title>
	<introduction>
		<p>
			We now endeavor to give a topological structure to an arbitrary product <m>\prod_{i\in I}X_i</m> of topological spaces.
			(See <xref ref="d_Ituple" text='global'/> and <xref ref="d_cartesian_product_arbitrary" text='global'/> for the definitions of arbitrary tuples and Cartesian products of sets.) As we will see, we can extend the finite product topology to this more general setting in two very different ways.
		</p>
	</introduction>


	<project xml:id="top_eg_arbitrary_product">
		<title>Product space (arbitrary)</title>
		<p>
			Let <m>\{X_i\}_{i\in I}</m> be a collection of topological spaces.
			We define two distinct topologies on the the product <m>X=\prod_{i\in I} X_i</m>.
			<ol>
				<li>
					<title>Box topology</title>
					<p>
						The <term>box topology</term> on <m>X</m> is the topology <m>\mathcal{T}_{\operatorname{box}}</m> generated by the basis
						<me>
							\mathcal{B}_{\operatorname{box}}=\left\{\prod_{i\in I}U_i\colon U_i \text{ open in } X_i\right\}
						</me>.
					</p>
				</li>

				<li>
					<title>Product topology</title>
					<p>
						The <term>product topology</term> on <m>X</m> is the topology <m>\mathcal{T}_{\operatorname{prod}}</m> generated by the basis
						<me>
							\mathcal{B}_{\operatorname{prod}}=\left\{\prod_{i\in I}U_i\colon U_i \text{ open in } X_i, U_i=X_i \text{ for all but finitely many } i\in I\right\}
						</me>.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
			We have <m>\mathcal{T}_{\operatorname{prod}}\subseteq \mathcal{T}_{\operatorname{box}}</m>; when the index set <m>I</m> is finite, we have <m>\mathcal{T}_{\operatorname{prod}}= \mathcal{T}_{\operatorname{box}}</m>.
		</p>


		<proof>
			<p>
				To see that both collections are indeed bases, observe that for any <m>x=(x_i)_{i\in I}</m> we have <m>x=(x_i)_{i\in I}\in \prod_{i\in I}X_i</m>, which is an element of <m>\mathcal{B}</m> in both cases; and that in both cases if we have <m>U=\prod_{i\in I}U_i</m>, <m>V=\prod_{i\in I}V_i\in \mathcal{B}</m>, then
				<me>
					\left(\prod_{i\in I}U_i \right)\times \left(\prod_{i\in I}V_i \right) =\prod_{i\in I}U_i\cap V_i
				</me>,
				is also an element of <m>\mathcal{B}</m>.
			</p>
		</proof>
	</project>

	<remark xml:id="rm_box_product">
		<title>Product coarser than box</title>
		<statement>
			<p>
				It is clear from the definition that we always have <m>\mathcal{B}_{\operatorname{prod}}\subseteq \mathcal{B}_{\operatorname{box}}</m>, and hence the product topology is coarser than (contained in) the box topology.
			</p>
		</statement>
	</remark>
	<convention>
	Following Munkres, given a set <m>A</m> and the special index set <m>I=\Z_+=\{1,2,3,\dots\}</m>, we write <m>A^\omega</m> for <m>A^{\Z_+}</m> as a shorthand.
	</convention>

	<example xml:id="eg_product_binary">
		<title>Infinite binary sequences</title>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Let
				<me>
					X=\{0,1\}^{\omega}=\prod_{i=1}^\infty \{0,1\}=\{(a_i)_{i=1}^n\colon a_i\in \{0,1\}\}
				</me>.

				<ol>
					<li>
						<p>
							Compare the box and product topologies on <m>X</m>, where <m>\{0,1\}</m> is given the discrete topology.
						</p>
					</li>

					<li>
						<p>
							Compare the box and product topologies on <m>X</m>, where <m>\{0,1\}</m> is given the trivial topology.
						</p>
					</li>
				</ol>
			</p>
		</statement>

		<solution>
			<p>
				As observed in <xref ref="top_eg_arbitrary_product"/>, the product topology is always contained in the box topology.
				Let's see whether the inclusion is strict in either case.
			</p>

			<ol>
				<li>
					<p>
						Assume <m>\{0,1\}</m> has the discrete topology.
						Since <m>\{1\}</m> is open in <m>\{0,1\}</m>, the set
						<me>
							U=\{1\}\times \{1\}\times \cdots =\{(1,1,\dots )\}
						</me>
						is open in the box topology.
						To see that it is not open in the product topology, take <m>x=(1,1,1,\dots, )</m> and let <m>V\in \mathcal{B}_{\operatorname{prod}}</m> contains <m>x</m>.
						By definition, we have
						<me>
							V=\prod_{i=1}^n V_i=V_1\times V_2\times \cdots \times V_N\times \{0,1\}\times \{0,1\}\times \cdots
						</me>
						for some <m>N</m>,
						where <m>V_{i}</m> is an open subset of <m>\{0,1\}</m>.
						Since <m>x\in V</m>, we have <m>\{1\}\subseteq V_i\ne\emptyset</m>.
						Since <m>V_i=\{0,1\}</m> for all <m>i\geq N</m>, the element <m>(1,1,\dots, 1,0,0,\dots)\in V</m>, from which it follows that <m>V\not\subseteq U</m>.
						We conclude that <m>U</m> is not a union of basis elements of the product topology, and hence is not open in the product topology.
					</p>

					<p>
						It is easy to see that <m>\{0,1\}^\Z</m> is discrete in the box topology.
						The argument above shows that <m>\{0,1\}^\Z</m> is not discrete in the product topology, since the singleton <m>\{(1,1,\dots, 1)\}</m> is not open.
					</p>
				</li>

				<li>
					<p>
						Now equip <m>\{0,1\}</m> with the trivial topology.
						Since the only open subsets of <m>\{0,1\}</m> are <m>\emptyset</m> and <m>\{0,1\}</m> it follows that a basis element <m>B=\prod_{i=1}^\infty U_i</m> in either topology is either empty (if <m>U_i=\emptyset</m> for <em>any</em> <m>i\in I</m>) or equal to <m>X</m> (if <m>U_i=\{0,1\}</m> for all <m>i\in I</m>).
						Since the bases of the two topologies are equal, the topologies are equal.
						Furthermore, since the only basis elements are <m>\emptyset</m> and <m>X</m>, the topology on <m>X</m> is just the trivial one: <ie />,
						we have <m>\mathcal{T}_{\operatorname{prod}}=\mathcal{T}_{\operatorname{box}}=\mathcal{T}_{\operatorname{trivial}}</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</solution>
	</example>

	<theorem xml:id="th_product_props">
		<title>Properties of product spaces</title>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Let <m>\{(X_i, \mathcal{T}_i)\}_{i\in I}</m> be a collection of topological spaces, and let <m>\mathcal{T}_{\operatorname{box}}, \mathcal{T}_{\operatorname{prod}}</m> be the box and product topologies on <m>X=\prod_{i\in I}X_i</m>.
			</p>

			<ol>
				<li>
					<p>
						Let <m>\mathcal{B}_i</m> be a basis for <m>\mathcal{T}_i</m> for all <m>i\in I</m>.
						The set
						<md>
							<mrow>\mathcal{B}_{\operatorname{box}} \amp =\left\{\prod_{i\in I}B_i\colon B_i\in \mathcal{B}_i\right\}</mrow>
						</md>
						is a basis for <m>\mathcal{T}_{\operatorname{box}}</m>.
					</p>

					<p>
						Similarly, the collection <m>\mathcal{B}_{\operatorname{prod}}</m> of all subsets of <m>X</m> of the form <m>\prod_{i\in I}U_i</m>, where <m>U_i=B_i\in \mathcal{B}_i</m> for all indices <m>i</m> in a finite set <m>J\subseteq I</m> and <m>U_i=X_i</m> for all <m>i\notin J</m>, is a basis for <m>\mathcal{T}_{\operatorname{prod}}</m>.
					</p>
				</li>

				<li>
					<p>
						Given subspaces <m>A_i\subseteq X_i</m> for all <m>i\in I</m>, let <m>A=\prod_{i\in I}A_i</m>.
						The box (resp., product) topology on <m>A</m> is equal to the box (resp., product) subspace topology on <m>A</m>.
					</p>
				</li>

				<li>
					<p>
						If <m>X_i</m> is Hausdorff (resp., <m>T_1</m>) for all <m>i\in I</m>, then <m>X=\prod_{i\in I}X_i</m> is Hausdorff (resp., <m>T_1</m>) with respect to both the box and product topologies.
					</p>
				</li>

				<li>
					<p>
						Given subsets <m>A_i\subseteq X_i</m> for all <m>i\in I</m>, we have
						<me>
							\prod_{i\in I}\overline{A_i}=\overline{\prod_{i\in I}A_i}
						</me>,
						where the closure on the right can be taken either with respect to box or product topology on <m>X=\prod_{i\in I}X_i</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</statement>


		<proof>
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p>
						We prove each basis axiom separately (for both the box and product basis).
					</p>

					<p>
						Axiom 1.
						Given <m>x=(x_i)_{i\in I}\in X</m>, we can find basis elements <m>B_i\in \mathcal{B}_{i}</m> containing <m>x_i</m>.
						We have
						<md>
							<mrow>x \amp\in B=\prod_{i\in I}B_i\in \mathcal{B}_{\operatorname{box}} </mrow>
							<mrow>x \amp\in B=\prod_{i\in I}X_i \in \mathcal{B}_{\operatorname{prod}} </mrow>
						</md>.
						Axiom 2.
						This axiom follows readily from the set theoretic fact that
						<me>
							\prod_{i\in I}U_i \cap \prod_{i\in I} V_i=\prod_{i\in I}U_i\cap V_i
						</me>.
						I'll leave the details to you.
					</p>
				</li>

				<li>
					<p>
						It helps to formulate this result in plain English: we wish to show that the subspace topology of the (box) product topology is equal to the (box) product topology of the subspace topologies. 
          </p>
          <p>Fix a choice of topology <m>\mathcal{T}\in \{\mathcal{T}_{\operatorname{box}}, \mathcal{T}_{\operatorname{prod}}\}</m>, let <m>\mathcal{B}\in \{\mathcal{B}_{\operatorname{box}}, \mathcal{B}_{\operatorname{prod}}\}</m> be the corresponding basis as defined in <xref ref="top_eg_arbitrary_product"/>, and let <m>\mathcal{T}_A</m> denote the corresponding subspace topology on <m>A</m>.
						Recall (<xref ref="th_subspace_props" text="global"/>) that <m>\mathcal{B}_A=\{B\cap A\colon B\in \mathcal{B}\}</m> is a basis for the subspace topology <m>\mathcal{T}_A</m>.
						Thus
            <mdn>
              <mrow> \amp </mrow>
            </mdn>
						<mdn>
							<mrow>\mathcal{B}_A \amp = \{B\cap A\colon B=\prod_{i\in I}U_i\in \mathcal{B}\} </mrow>
							<mrow xml:id="eq_subpace_prod"> \amp = \left\{ \prod_{i\in I}U_i\cap A_i\colon \prod_{i\in I}U_i\in \mathcal{B}\right\}
              </mrow>
						</mdn>,
						where the last equality follows from the set theory identity 
						<me>
							\prod_{i\in I}U_i\cap \prod_{i\in I}A_i=\prod_{i\in I}U_i\cap A_i
						</me>.
            Now observe that when <m>\mathcal{B}=\mathcal{B}_{\operatorname{box}}</m> the set in <xref ref="eq_subpace_prod"/> is precisely the basis for the box product topology on the subspaces <m>(A_i, \mathcal{T}_{i, A_i})</m> as described in <xref ref="top_eg_arbitrary_product"/>; and similarly, when <m>\mathcal{B}=\mathcal{B}_{\operatorname{prod}}</m> the set in <xref ref="eq_subpace_prod"/> is the basis for the product topology on the subspaces <m>(A_i, \mathcal{T}_{i, A_i})</m>. 
					</p>
          <p>
            Going back to our plan English formulation, we have shown that the subspace topology of the (box) product topology and the (box) product topology of the subspace topologies share a common basis (<xref ref="eq_subpace_prod"/>). It follows that the topologies themselves are equal. 
          </p>
				</li>

				<li>
					<p>
						Assume <m>X_i</m> is Hausdorff for all <m>i\in I</m>.
						If <m>x=(x_i)_{i\in I}</m> and <m>y=(y_i)_{i\in I}</m> are distinct, then we have <m>x_{i_0}\ne y_{i_0}</m> for some <m>i_0\in I</m>.
						Since <m>X_{i_0}</m> is Hausdorff, there are disjoint open neighborhoods <m>U_{i_0}, V_{i_0}</m> of <m>x_{i_0}, y_{i_0}</m> in <m>X_{i_0}</m>.
						The sets <m>U=U_{i_0}\times \prod_{i\ne i_0}X_i, V=V_{i_0}\times \prod_{i\ne i_0}X_i</m>,
						are disjoint open basis elements for both topologies containing <m>x, y</m>, respectively.
						Thus <m>X</m> is Hausdorff.
						The proof for the <m>T_1</m> statement is similar.
					</p>
				</li>

				<li>
					<p>
						We prove the equality by showing
						<me>
							x\notin \prod_{i\in I}\overline{A_i} \iff x\notin \overline{\prod_{i\in I}A_i}
						</me>.
						<m>(\implies)</m>.
						If <m>x=(x_i)_{i\in I}\notin \prod_{i\in I}\overline{A_i}</m>, there is an index <m>i_0\in I</m> such that <m>x_{i_0}\notin \overline{A_{i_0}}</m>, and thus an open set <m>U_{i_0}\ni x_{i_0}</m> such that <m>U_{i_0}\cap A_{i_0}=\emptyset</m>.
						The set <m>U_{i_0}\times \prod_{i\ne i_0}X_i</m>
						is open in both topologies (box and product), contains <m>x=(x_i)_{i\in I}</m>, and is disjoint with <m>\prod_{i\in I}A_i</m>.
						We conclude that <m>x\notin \overline{\prod_{i\in I}A_i}</m> in both topologies.
					</p>

					<p>
						<m>(\impliedby)</m>.
						If <m>x=(x_i)_{i\in I}\notin \overline{\prod_{i\in I}A_i}</m> there is an open basis element <m>B=\prod_{i\in I}U_i</m> in the topology (box or product) containing <m>x</m> that is disjoint with <m>\prod_{i\in I}A_i</m>.
						It follows that we must have <m>U_{i_0}\cap A_{i_0}=\emptyset</m> for some <m>i_0\in I</m> and open <m>U_{i_0}\subseteq X_{i_0}</m>, and thus that <m>x_{i_0}\notin \overline{A_{i_0}}</m>.
						We conclude that <m>x\notin \prod_{i\in I}\overline{A_i}</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</proof>
	</theorem>
</section>
